text: Why do writers/directors always make otherwise intelligent science-types predictably violate quarantine procedures that invariably go horribly wrong, ruining the mission itself?  It really is annoyingly routine now and demonstrates a critical lack of creativity on their part.  Using human curiosity as an undeniable force that compels "scientists" to ignore a basic law of research and exploration is such a distraction that it ruins the basic premise of a movie.  Really, this started with Howard Hawks' "The Thing" in 1951.  Flash forward to "Alien" where Ash (the robot science officer) does the deed that ends up dooming the crew - and continues with his progeny doing the same thing in "Prometheus", and this trope has gotten very old.  When a writer/director pisses off his intelligent viewers and demonstrates a low IQ in his characters, it results in a bad taste in our mouths, bad reviews and unprofitable movies that depend on dramatic scores, sound effects, star-power instead of plot.
